{"source_key":"sha256-f88bd5c54ac5fbbfc982c6d403b2565f","record_index":753,"record_hash":"sha256:7b2ec91b30ff399dbe148f031883a96bf2877340e1b66b36b4ad3afc8f90f3e1","timestamp":"2026-05-24T15:12:26.346Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 6db949\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 3152\nOutput:\nconfiguration, SSRF protections, credential boundaries, and a separate privacy\nreview. They must not be accepted as user-supplied request parameters.\n\nRecommended split:\n\n- Forge owns PR URL parsing, access checks, snapshot generation, caching, and UI\n- `git-meta-lib` or a small shared helper owns GitMeta transport/fetch details\n- `but-agentlog` owns interpretation of GitButler agentlog keys and records\n\nIf the metadata ref is missing or cannot be fetched, the page should show a\nclear empty state rather than treating the PR as having no agent work:\n\n```text\nNo Agent Trail metadata was found for this public pull request.\n```\n\nThat distinction matters because \"not fetchable\" and \"no captured sessions\"\nmean different things.\n\nThe exact local ref name used for the fetched metadata is an implementation\ndetail between the GitMeta helper and `but-agentlog`. The important contract is\nthat snapshot generation reads from the resolved metadata OID, not from a moving\nref that can change mid-request.\n\n## Relationship Model\n\nOne pull request may relate to many sessions. One session may relate to many\npull requests or branches.\n\nThe durable object remains the project-scoped session. Pull requests, reviews,\nand branches should reference session or turn keys; they should not own copies\nof transcript records. Change targets remain available in `but-agentlog`, but\nAgent Trail v1 does not query them.\n\nThe first Agent Trail implementation can start from:\n\n1. pull request number as a `review` target, such as\n   `gitbutler-review:13936`\n2.